name: 3,5-dibromobenzaldehyde
Reason: To predict the melting point of 3,5-dibromobenzaldehyde, we analyze the influences of the substituents attached to the benzene ring. The base structure is benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C. Bromine as a substituent is a heavy halogen, generally increasing the melting point due to increased molecular weight and the resulting higher van der Waals forces. Each bromine could be considered to add roughly +60-70°C due to these interactions. The aldehyde group (-CHO) typically increases the melting point because it can form hydrogen bonds and has a polar character, which might contribute around +20-30°C. Two bromines and one aldehyde give us 3 substituents to consider. However, given the close proximity of the substituents (3,5-disubstitution), they might sterically hinder each other slightly reducing the overall increase due to some destabilization of the crystal lattice. Hence, the total increase may be slightly less than simply summing the individual contributions of each group.
